at|Only UTF-8 encoding is supported by ^*baaBridge^*n.  This is increasingly becoming the go to choice for supporting International characters for web pages and for small files distributed on the net.

All good modern 'text only' editors support UTF-8. For example my choice for Windows is the Free  Notepad++  from ^*h https://notepad-plus-plus.org/ ^*n.   So just write your .lin file using any of the supported character sets (see earlier).

It works so easily because BOTH Java and modern OS'es  (Windows, MAC and Linux)  have built in support but you will need to use UTF-8 encoding.  You DO NOT need to have the UTF-8 BOM (Byte Order Mark) at the front of the file.  If present aaBridge will ignore it.  In Java the built-in support comes from an internal 'multi-script' font called 'Dialog'.    
^c^*baaBridge will |cp|red|at|^*b automatically ^*b|cp||at| use the Java Dialog font for ANY and ALL international characters.^*n  

To change size of your International text you can use a normal .lin Font description with the size you want.  
